# reference-delivery example — operator-editable configuration (NO SECRETS).
#
# This file is sourced by run.sh. It carries only the knobs an operator may
# change; the launch script translates these into the production
# temper-daemon / smith-worker / temper-provision-forgejo CLI flags. CLI
# overrides always win over what is set here, which in turn overrides the
# binaries' own defaults.
#
# Secrets (per-role tokens/passwords, any API key) never live here — see
# ../secrets/ and ../secrets/.env.example.
#
# The reference-delivery demo keeps the richer workflow shape: architect,
# engineer, and reviewer are served by one worker; owner and human remain
# workflow-declared but unserved. Human is still the workflow intake author, so
# the provisioner files seeded intake as that provisioned external-filer user.

# --- Repository ---------------------------------------------------------------
# Legacy single-repo knobs. If REPOS is left empty, run.sh provisions and scans
# exactly OWNER/NAME. They remain useful for compatibility and quick one-repo
# smoke runs:
#   REPOS= ./run.sh start
OWNER=acme
NAME=service

# Repository set for the single daemon + single worker. Leave REPOS empty to use
# OWNER/NAME (the default one-repo converging path). Set it to several
# space-separated "owner/name" paths to exercise multi-repo scanning and
# cross-repo fan-out, for example:
#   REPOS="acme/service acme/canary"
# Duplicate entries are ignored; every entry must be owner/name.
REPOS=

# Default branch the repos are initialized with (implementation PRs target it).
DEFAULT_BRANCH=main

# --- Workflow spec ------------------------------------------------------------
# The reference-delivery spec. run.sh passes this file to the provisioner and the
# daemon via Temper's --workflow flag. It tracks the canonical Temper fixture
# crates/temper-workflow/fixtures/reference-delivery.json — keep semantics in
# sync; do not fork the workflow here.
#
# Path is resolved relative to this example's config/ directory by run.sh.
WORKFLOW_FILE=workflow.json

# --- Served roles -------------------------------------------------------------
# Roles serviced by the daemon (--role) and worker (--capability). Each must be a
# provisioned workflow role. Deliberately do NOT include owner or human here: they
# are declared in the workflow, but this demo leaves them idle as the safe
# no-worker state.
SERVED_ROLES="architect engineer reviewer"

# --- Seeded intake issue ------------------------------------------------------
# The ordinary per-repo intake issue the provisioned human (external filer) files
# when CROSS_REPO_INTAKE is off. It is DELIBERATELY THIN: the filer declares only
# the overall intent, with no acceptance criteria, no setting name, and no
# implementation detail. The architect's triage rewrite is the demo proof.
#
# INTAKE_BODY_FILE is resolved relative to this config/ directory by run.sh.
INTAKE_TITLE='Service banner should identify the environment'
INTAKE_BODY_FILE=intake-issue.md

# Cross-repo intake seeding:
#   auto  seed one parent in the first repo when REPOS has 2+ repos; otherwise
#         seed ordinary per-repo intake.
#   1     force cross-repo parent mode (requires 2+ repos).
#   0     seed ordinary per-repo intake for every configured repo.
# In cross-repo mode, only the first repo receives an intake. Its body carries a
# machine-written plan with one plain owner/name `target_repo` per configured
# repo; the architect returns needs_breakdown children for the daemon to create in
# their target repos. Non-first repos are provisioned without duplicate intake.
CROSS_REPO_INTAKE=auto
CROSS_REPO_INTAKE_TITLE="Coordinate greeting across service and canary"

# --- Forgejo + daemon endpoints ----------------------------------------------
# Where the bundled throwaway Forgejo server listens. The default intentionally
# avoids the common local Forgejo port 3000.
BASE_URL=http://127.0.0.1:4200

# Where the single temper-daemon listens for both worker protocol traffic and the
# Forgejo webhook route. Leave WEBHOOK_URL empty to derive it from DAEMON_BIND;
# override only when Forgejo must reach the daemon through a different address.
DAEMON_BIND=127.0.0.1:38200
WEBHOOK_URL=

# Long role poll backstop so webhooks demonstrably drive progress; short
# mechanical cadence because Forgejo 7.0.x has no Actions-completion webhook and
# landing needs CI-read polling.
DAEMON_POLL_CADENCE_SECS=120
DAEMON_MECHANICAL_CADENCE_SECS=2
DAEMON_LEASE_TTL_SECS=300

# Hard backstop on how long the launcher blocks before tearing the run down.
RUN_SECS=600

# --- CPU cap (lesson 0009) ----------------------------------------------------
# The bundled Forgejo server (a Go program) can drive the host to several cores
# of sustained CPU under this multi-process workload. Cap GOMAXPROCS so the Go
# runtime cannot exceed this many cores. Set empty to opt out. Default 2.
TEMPER_FORGEJO_GOMAXPROCS=2

# --- Cached pinned binaries ---------------------------------------------------
# Absolute paths to the pinned Forgejo (7.0.12) and forgejo-runner (3.5.1)
# binaries. Leave empty to let the first run download + checksum them into
# .cache/forgejo/ (needs network to Codeberg / code.forgejo.org). On an
# offline/sandboxed host, pre-stage the binaries and point these at them.
TEMPER_FORGEJO_BINARY=
TEMPER_FORGEJO_RUNNER_BINARY=

# --- Temper entry-point binaries ---------------------------------------------
# The example targets Temper's operator-facing root-package entry points. Leave
# empty for the workspace target/debug defaults. TEMPER_BUILD_PACKAGE is the
# package run.sh builds in the development profile unless TEMPER_SKIP_BUILD=1.
TEMPER_DAEMON_BIN=
TEMPER_PROVISION_BIN=
TEMPER_VALIDATE_BIN=
TEMPER_BUILD_PACKAGE=temper

# --- Smith worker + coding agent ---------------------------------------------
# Smith supplies the consolidated worker tier. Leave SMITH_WORKER_BIN empty for
# target/debug/smith-worker. WORKER_MAX_CONCURRENT=1 keeps the demo deterministic.
SMITH_WORKSPACE_ROOT=
SMITH_BUILD_PACKAGE=smith-temper-agent-cli
SMITH_WORKER_BIN=
WORKER_MAX_CONCURRENT=1

# REFERENCE_DELIVERY_CODER selects the coding executor's agent command:
#   smith    (default) the real pi-SDK workspace agent (smith-coding-agent),
#            built from this Smith checkout. The architect returns ready_code or
#            needs_breakdown, the engineer leaves a real product diff, and the
#            reviewer approves/requests changes. Provider/auth come from
#            SMITH_CODING_AGENT_ARGS (default `--auth chatgpt-oauth`).
#   greeting the deterministic stand-in (tools/greeting-coder.sh): fixed triage,
#            breakdown, review, and src/banner.sh behavior with no LLM — for an
#            offline smoke run of the full daemon/worker topology.
REFERENCE_DELIVERY_CODER=smith
# Override the auto-built agent binary / its CLI args (provider + auth) when
# REFERENCE_DELIVERY_CODER=smith. Empty uses the built debug binary and
# `--auth chatgpt-oauth`.
SMITH_CODING_AGENT_BIN=
SMITH_CODING_AGENT_ARGS=

# For Smith provider/auth setup, run Smith's documented preflight commands from
# the Smith checkout and edit SMITH_CODING_AGENT_ARGS / secrets/.env as needed.
# Temper and smith-worker do not read provider auth files or provider secrets.
